{:metadata {:description [{"text" "<p>This entry represents a family of proteins from plants and bacteria that belong to the helicase superfamily 2 (SF2), including ATP-dependent DNA helicase RecG and Transcription-repair-coupling factor (Mfd) [[cite:PUB00102295]].</p>\n\n<p>RecG plays a critical role in recombination and DNA repair both in plants and bacteria. It helps to process Holliday junction intermediates to mature products by catalysing branch migration. It has a DNA unwinding activity characteristic of a DNA helicase with a 3'- to 5'- polarity [[cite:PUB00060423]]. RecG unwind branched duplex DNA (Y-DNA) and has a role in constitutive stable DNA replication (CsdR) and R-loop formation [[cite:PUB00060423], [cite:PUB00060424], [cite:PUB00025306]]. It is genetically synergistic to RadA and RuvABC [[cite:PUB00098842]]. The structure of the Thermatoga maritima RecG protein shows three distinct domains with an α-β configuration, the largest N-terminal Domain 1 which interacts with DNA junctions, and Domains 2 and 3 at the C-terminal which contain the characteristic motifs that identify RecG as an SF2 helicase [[cite:PUB00025306]].</p>", "llm" false, "checked" false, "updated" false}], :is-reviewed-llm false, :representative-structure nil, :overlaps-with [{"accession" "IPR027417", "name" "P-loop containing nucleoside triphosphate hydrolase", "type" "homologous_superfamily"}], :member-databases {"panther" {"PTHR47964" "ATP-DEPENDENT DNA HELICASE HOMOLOG RECG, CHLOROPLASTIC"}}, :is-updated-llm false, :name {"name" "ATP-dependent DNA helicase RecG/Transcription-repair-coupling factor", "short" "RecG/Mfd"}, :wikipedia nil, :source-database "interpro", :type "family", :counters {"structures" 17, "domain_architectures" 0, "proteomes" 9409, "taxa" 38037, "subfamilies" 0, "interactions" 0, "matches" 89567, "sets" 0, "proteins" 89567, "structural_models" {"alphafold" 67202}, "pathways" 1}, :integrated nil, :cross-references {"ec" {"displayName" "ENZYME", "description" "ENZ